DESPITE bullish transactions on the floor of the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) on Friday after market indices rose by 1.25 per cent at the close of business, equities trading ends the week with 0.41 per cent loss. The equities market sustained its lacklustre performance last week, amidst continued risk-off sentiments and the absence of positive market catalysts, says Cordros analysts. With losses recorded in two of the three trading sessions in the shortened week due to festive season, the All-share index shed 0.41 per cent to settle the Month-to-date and Year-to-Date losses at 2.17 per cent and 15.95 per cent, respectively. Dangote Cement to buy back shares Nigerian Tribune bags DAME’s Lifetime Achievement… Meet ‘The Soft One’, qualified to satisfy you Wife of drowned RCCG pastor blames hotel for tragedy, hires… On Sectoral performances, the Banking and Industrial Goods recorded declines at 0.26 per cent and 0.31 per cent respectively, following selloffs of Guaranty Trust Bank at -2.0 per cent and CCNN at -3.0 per cent. Conversely, Consumer Goods, Insurance, and Oil & Gas edged higher at 1.3 per cent, 1.0 per cent and 0.7 per cent respectively, driven by gains in Nestle at 10 per cent, NEM at 2.2 per cent and Oando 6.76 per cent. For the remaining two day trading of equities in the year 2019, Analysts posit the level of activity and volatility being sustained, with some pockets of gains expected, as fund and portfolio managers realign portfolios prior to the start of 2020. SHOCKING LIFE STORY!!! Abuja Man reveals (FREE) secret Fruits that Increased his Manh0d size and Lasting Power in just 7days… CLICK HERE
